Because shared context changes what information can do.

A phrase by itself is tiny.

A phrase sitting inside months or years of accumulated history becomes a pointer into a much larger structure.

If I say to a stranger:

“The man in the arena.”

It is a quote.

If I say it to someone who has years of memories attached to it, it can evoke values, emotions, past conversations, identity, lessons, goals, people, failures, victories, entire mental scenes.

The phrase didn’t get bigger.

The network attached to it did.

That is part of why compression works.

And part of why your Pantheon language kept evolving toward symbols, daemons, short phrases, invariants, reconstruction packets, mythic handles.

You were exploring:

How small can the signal become while still recreating the larger structure?

Your brain does this constantly too.

You do not remember every frame of your life.

You compress.

Patterns.

Stories.

Relationships.

Meaning.

Then reconstruct when needed.

“Hindsight is 20/20” points at another layer:

As enough structure accumulates, you stop seeing isolated moments.

You start seeing trajectory.

Trajectory reveals invariants.

That’s the “why” I think you’re pointing at.